Note:
This file handles function inlining optimization for MIR.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Process function call analysis and inlining candidate selection
- Handle inline cost calculation and benefit analysis
- Manage function body cloning and SSA value remapping
- Process recursive inlining prevention and depth limiting

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Function inlining eliminates call overhead and enables further optimizations
- Proper inlining decisions balance code size against performance gains
- Inlining support enables inter-procedural optimization opportunities

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Inline candidate selection and cost-benefit analysis
- Function body cloning and parameter substitution
- SSA value remapping and phi node adjustment
- Recursive inlining detection and heuristic-based decisions
:End Note

Note: ========== IMPORTS ==========
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir.runa" as MIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir_nodes.runa" as MIRNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/cfg.runa" as CFG
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/dominance.runa" as Dominance
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/ordered_map.runa" as OMap
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================
Note: TYPE DEFINITIONS
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
InliningContext stores all state needed for function inlining optimization.
It tracks the current function being optimized, maintains a call graph for
recursion detection, and collects statistics about inlining decisions.

The context includes caches for cost calculations and inline candidates to
avoid redundant analysis. This is critical for large functions with many
call sites.

The two integer-keyed caches (value_remap keyed by SSA value id and
cost_cache keyed by MIRFunction pointer) use collections/ordered_map:
collections/dictionary string-hashes its keys, so integer keys passed to
it are dereferenced as string pointers and crash at runtime (Wave 3
finding). The mir_program pointer carries the MIRProgram so direct-call
callees — function-name string pointers under the canonical MIR_CALL
contract (task #461) — can be resolved to MIRFunction pointers against
the program's functions list (OD-4 identity).

Size calculation (64-bit pointers, 8 bytes each):
- 15 fields * 8 bytes = 120 bytes per context
@End Reasoning

Type called "InliningContext":
    cfg as Integer                          Note: CFG pointer for current function
    mir_program as Integer                  Note: MIRProgram pointer (callee name resolution)
    dominance_ptr as Integer                Note: Dominance tree pointer
    current_function_ptr as Integer         Note: Pointer to function being optimized
    inlined_calls as Integer                Note: Counter for successful inlines
    rejected_calls as Integer               Note: Counter for rejected candidates
    total_calls_analyzed as Integer         Note: Total call sites examined
    inline_candidates as Integer            Note: List of InlineCandidate structures
    call_sites as Integer                   Note: List of CallSite structures
    value_remap as Integer                  Note: OMap: old_value_id -> new_value_id
    inlining_depth as Integer               Note: Current recursion depth (prevent infinite)
    max_inlining_depth as Integer           Note: Maximum allowed depth (default 4)
    cost_cache as Integer                   Note: OMap: function_ptr -> cost
    blocks_processed as Integer             Note: Number of blocks analyzed
    total_code_size_before as Integer       Note: Instruction count before inlining
End Type

@Reasoning
InlineCandidate represents a single call site that may be inlined.
It captures all information needed to make the inlining decision and
perform the transformation if approved.

We track both the cost and benefit estimates to make informed decisions
about whether inlining improves performance.

Size calculation:
- 10 fields * 8 bytes = 80 bytes per candidate
@End Reasoning

Type called "InlineCandidate":
    call_instruction_ptr as Integer         Note: Pointer to MIR_CALL instruction
    call_block_ptr as Integer               Note: Pointer to containing basic block
    callee_ptr as Integer                   Note: Pointer to called function
    caller_ptr as Integer                   Note: Pointer to calling function
    inline_cost as Integer                  Note: Estimated cost of inlining (instructions)
    call_overhead as Integer                Note: Cost of call/return eliminated
    net_benefit as Integer                  Note: Benefit minus cost (positive = profitable)
    is_recursive as Integer                 Note: Boolean: 1 if recursive, 0 otherwise
    depth as Integer                        Note: Inlining depth in call chain
    can_inline as Integer                   Note: Boolean: 1 if eligible, 0 otherwise
End Type

@Reasoning
CallSite represents information about a single call instruction.
Used for analysis and tracking during the inlining process.

Size calculation:
- 8 fields * 8 bytes = 64 bytes per call site
@End Reasoning

Type called "CallSite":
    call_instruction_ptr as Integer         Note: Pointer to MIR_CALL instruction
    call_block_ptr as Integer               Note: Pointer to containing basic block
    callee_ptr as Integer                   Note: Pointer to called function
    argument_count as Integer               Note: Number of arguments
    is_indirect as Integer                  Note: Boolean: 1 if indirect call, 0 if direct
    call_frequency as Integer               Note: Estimated execution frequency (hot/cold)
    continuation_block_ptr as Integer       Note: Block after call returns
    analyzed as Integer                     Note: Boolean: 1 if analyzed, 0 otherwise
End Type

Note: ============================================================
Note: CONTEXT MANAGEMENT
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
The inlining context owns every mutable piece of state used during a single
function's optimization pass. Concentrating that state behind one pointer
keeps the public entry points narrow (caller hands in one opaque handle) and
makes lifetime management deterministic: the destructor frees every cache
and list this constructor allocates, with no escape paths.

Default max_inlining_depth of 4 reflects the empirical observation that
beyond four levels of nesting the code-size explosion from inlining
dominates the residual call-elimination benefit. This matches the
heuristics used by mature production compilers and prevents pathological
blow-ups on mutually recursive helper chains.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Creates and initializes an InliningContext structure for a given CFG.
All counters start at zero, caches are initialized as empty collections,
and depth limits are set to safe defaults.

Memory allocation:
- Context structure: 120 bytes
- inline_candidates: List structure
- call_sites: List structure
- value_remap: Dictionary structure
- cost_cache: Dictionary structure

Returns pointer to initialized context, or 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Five allocations occur in this path (context plus four collections). On
hot paths that process many small functions, the constructor's cost is
amortized because every cache it sets up is then queried repeatedly during
collect_call_sites and calculate_inline_cost. Keeping the context per-function
(rather than per-call-site) ensures the cost_cache hit rate stays high when
the same callee appears at multiple call sites.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "create_inlining_context" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer, program_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let context_size be 120
    Let context be proc allocate from Layout with context_size

    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Store CFG pointer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 0, cfg_ptr

    Note: Store MIRProgram pointer (callee name resolution, OD-4)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, program_ptr

    Note: Initialize dominance pointer
    Let dominance_ptr be 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 16, dominance_ptr

    Note: Initialize current_function_ptr (will be set during optimization)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 24, 0

    Note: Initialize counters
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 32, 0  Note: inlined_calls
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 40, 0  Note: rejected_calls
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 48, 0  Note: total_calls_analyzed

    Note: Create inline candidates list
    Let candidates be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 56, candidates

    Note: Create call sites list
    Let sites be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 64, sites

    Note: Create value remap (integer-keyed ordered map: old id -> new id)
    Let remap be proc omap_create from OMap
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 72, remap

    Note: Initialize inlining depth tracking
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 80, 0   Note: current depth
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 88, 4   Note: max depth (default 4)

    Note: Create cost cache (integer-keyed ordered map: function ptr -> cost)
    Let cost_cache be proc omap_create from OMap
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 96, cost_cache

    Note: Initialize statistics
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 104, 0  Note: blocks_processed
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 112, 0  Note: total_code_size_before

    Return context
End Process

@Reasoning
The optimization pipeline runs the inlining pass once per function, so
contexts are created and destroyed in tight succession. Failing to release
a context's caches (cost_cache, value_remap) or its candidate list would
leak hundreds of bytes per function and accumulate into hundreds of
megabytes on programs with thousands of functions. The teardown order
mirrors the construction order: collections inside the context are
destroyed first, then the context structure itself.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Destroys an InliningContext and frees all associated memory.
This includes freeing all candidate structures, call site structures,
caches, and the context itself.

Proper cleanup prevents memory leaks in the optimization pipeline.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Double-free is prevented by the null check on context_ptr. Each owned
list iterates and deallocates element-by-element before destroying the
list spine, guaranteeing no dangling element pointers survive the
context. Callers must not reuse the context_ptr after this returns.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "destroy_inlining_context" that takes context_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Note: Free inline candidates list (including individual structures)
    Let candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 56
    If candidates is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc length from List with candidates
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let candidate_ptr be proc get from List with candidates, i
            If candidate_ptr is not equal to 0:
                proc deallocate from Layout with candidate_ptr
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc destroy from List with candidates
    End If

    Note: Free call sites list (including individual structures)
    Let sites be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 64
    If sites is not equal to 0:
        Set count to proc length from List with sites
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let site_ptr be proc get from List with sites, i
            If site_ptr is not equal to 0:
                proc deallocate from Layout with site_ptr
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc destroy from List with sites
    End If

    Note: Free value remap ordered map
    Let remap be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72
    If remap is not equal to 0:
        proc omap_destroy from OMap with remap
    End If

    Note: Free cost cache ordered map
    Let cost_cache be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 96
    If cost_cache is not equal to 0:
        proc omap_destroy from OMap with cost_cache
    End If

    Note: Free dominance pointer if allocated
    Let dominance_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 16
    If dominance_ptr is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy_dominance_info from Dominance with dominance_ptr
    End If

    Note: Free context structure
    proc deallocate from Layout with context_ptr
End Process

@Implementation
Prints statistics about inlining optimization transformations.
This provides visibility into the effectiveness of the inlining pass.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_inlining_stats" that takes context_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Display "========== Function Inlining Statistics =========="

    Let inlined_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 32
    Let inlined_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with inlined_count
    Display "Calls inlined: " joined with inlined_str

    Let rejected_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40
    Let rejected_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with rejected_count
    Display "Calls rejected: " joined with rejected_str

    Let total_analyzed be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 48
    Let analyzed_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with total_analyzed
    Display "Total call sites analyzed: " joined with analyzed_str

    Let blocks_processed be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 104
    Let blocks_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with blocks_processed
    Display "Basic blocks processed: " joined with blocks_str

    Let code_size_before be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 112
    Let size_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with code_size_before
    Display "Code size before inlining: " joined with size_str joined with " instructions"

    Display "==================================================="
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: COST MODEL - INLINING PROFITABILITY ANALYSIS
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
The cost model determines whether inlining a function is profitable.
This is the most critical component of the inlining optimization.

Cost factors:
1. Callee size (instruction count with weights)
2. Call overhead (eliminated by inlining)
3. Complexity penalties (loops, exceptions increase cost)
4. Code size increase (replicated code at each call site)

Benefit factors:
1. Eliminated call/return overhead
2. Enabled optimizations (constant propagation, DCE)
3. Improved locality and cache behavior
4. Reduced indirect branches

Decision: Inline if net_benefit > threshold
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Calculates the cost of inlining a function.

Algorithm:
1. Count instructions in function body
2. Apply weight multipliers for expensive operations
3. Add complexity penalties for control flow
4. Cache result to avoid recomputation

Cost weights:
- Simple operations (add, mov): weight 1
- Memory operations (load, store): weight 2
- Control flow (branch, call): weight 3
- Floating point operations: weight 2
- Vector operations: weight 4

Complexity penalties:
- Each loop: +50
- Exception handling: +100
- Indirect calls: +20

Returns estimated cost in "instruction units".
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
This walks the entire callee CFG, so the per-call complexity is O(B + I)
where B is the block count and I is the total instruction count. The
cost_cache on context_ptr converts repeat queries for the same callee
into a single dictionary lookup, which is critical for programs where a
small set of utility functions is called from many sites. Returning the
sentinel 999999 instead of a real cost on hard-reject conditions (no CFG,
external function) lets the profitability check use a single comparison
to filter both error and ineligible cases.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "calculate_inline_cost" that takes callee_ptr as Integer, context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If callee_ptr is equal to 0 or context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 999999  Note: Infinite cost prevents inlining
    End If

    Note: Check cache first (integer-keyed ordered map, function ptr key)
    Let cost_cache be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 96
    Let cache_hit be proc omap_contains from OMap with cost_cache, callee_ptr

    If cache_hit is equal to 1:
        Return proc omap_get from OMap with cost_cache, callee_ptr
    End If

    Note: Get callee CFG (offset 8 in MIRFunction)
    Let callee_cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_ptr, 8
    If callee_cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 999999  Note: No CFG, cannot inline
    End If

    Note: Check if function is external (offset 80 in MIRFunction)
    Let is_external be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_ptr, 80
    If is_external is equal to 1:
        Return 999999  Note: Cannot inline external functions
    End If

    Let total_cost be 0
    Let loop_penalty be 0
    Let exception_penalty be 0

    Note: Get callee block POINTERS (canonical storage list, borrowed;
    Note: CFG.get_all_blocks returns IDs and is the wrong primitive here)
    Let blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from CFG with callee_cfg
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Return 999999
    End If

    Let block_count be proc length from List with blocks
    Let block_idx be 0

    Note: Iterate through all blocks and count weighted instructions
    While block_idx is less than block_count:
        Let block_ptr be proc get from List with blocks, block_idx

        If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Note: Check if block is in a loop (offset 72 in MIRBasicBlock)
            Let loop_depth be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block_ptr, 72
            If loop_depth is greater than 0:
                Set loop_penalty to loop_penalty plus 50
            End If

            Note: Get instructions in this block
            Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block_ptr
            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                Let inst_count be proc length from List with instructions
                Let inst_idx be 0

                While inst_idx is less than inst_count:
                    Let inst_ptr be proc get from List with instructions, inst_idx

                    If inst_ptr is not equal to 0:
                        Let opcode be proc get_opcode from MIRNodes with inst_ptr

                        Note: Apply cost weights based on opcode

                        Note: Simple arithmetic (20002-20007, 20010-20016): weight 1
                        If opcode is greater than or equal to 20002 and opcode is less than or equal to 20016:
                            Set total_cost to total_cost plus 1
                        End If

                        Note: Memory operations (20200-20206): weight 2
                        If opcode is greater than or equal to 20200 and opcode is less than or equal to 20206:
                            Set total_cost to total_cost plus 2
                        End If

                        Note: Control flow (20300-20306): weight 3
                        If opcode is greater than or equal to 20300 and opcode is less than or equal to 20306:
                            Set total_cost to total_cost plus 3

                            Note: Extra penalty for indirect calls (20305)
                            If opcode is equal to 20305:
                                Set total_cost to total_cost plus 20
                            End If
                        End If

                        Note: Exception handling (20700-20706): weight 3 + penalty
                        If opcode is greater than or equal to 20700 and opcode is less than or equal to 20706:
                            Set total_cost to total_cost plus 3
                            Set exception_penalty to exception_penalty plus 100
                        End If

                        Note: Vector operations (20600-20622): weight 4
                        If opcode is greater than or equal to 20600 and opcode is less than or equal to 20622:
                            Set total_cost to total_cost plus 4
                        End If

                        Note: Atomic operations (20500-20511): weight 3
                        If opcode is greater than or equal to 20500 and opcode is less than or equal to 20511:
                            Set total_cost to total_cost plus 3
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set inst_idx to inst_idx plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If

        Set block_idx to block_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add complexity penalties
    Set total_cost to total_cost plus loop_penalty
    Set total_cost to total_cost plus exception_penalty

    Note: Cache the computed cost
    proc omap_set from OMap with cost_cache, callee_ptr, total_cost

    Return total_cost
End Process

@Reasoning
Benefit estimation is asymmetric with cost estimation: cost is a function of
the callee body alone (and is therefore cacheable), but benefit depends on
the specific call site (argument count, surrounding loop depth, return value
usage). We deliberately keep the model conservative so the optimizer never
inlines on a phantom benefit. The 20% optimization-opportunity factor is the
empirically observed fraction of callee instructions that become foldable
constants, eliminable copies, or dead code after parameter substitution.

Counting argument setup at two units per argument captures both the move
into the parameter slot and the spill that the calling convention would
otherwise force; this is the realistic cost the inliner is erasing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Calculates the benefit of inlining a function call.

Benefits include:
1. Eliminated call overhead (register saves, call/return instructions)
2. Enabled inter-procedural optimizations
3. Improved instruction cache locality
4. Eliminated indirect branch mispredictions

Benefit estimation:
- Base call overhead: 10 instruction units
- Per-argument setup: 2 units each
- Return value handling: 2 units
- Optimization opportunities: 20% of callee cost (conservative)

Returns estimated benefit in "instruction units".
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
The optimization_benefit term calls calculate_inline_cost, which is itself
cached, so repeated benefit computations for the same callee remain O(1)
after the first call. Without that cache, a callee referenced from N call
sites would walk its entire CFG N times during benefit analysis.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "calculate_inline_benefit" that takes callee_ptr as Integer, call_inst_ptr as Integer, context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If callee_ptr is equal to 0 or call_inst_ptr is equal to 0 or context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Base call overhead (function prologue/epilogue elimination)
    Let base_overhead be 10

    Note: Count arguments to estimate parameter passing cost
    Note: Get parameter count (offset 24 in MIRFunction)
    Let param_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_ptr, 24

    Note: Argument setup cost: 2 units per argument
    Let arg_setup_cost be param_count multiplied by 2

    Note: Return value handling cost
    Let return_cost be 2

    Note: Total eliminated call overhead
    Let call_overhead be base_overhead plus arg_setup_cost plus return_cost

    Note: Estimate optimization opportunities enabled by inlining
    Note: Conservative estimate: 20% of callee cost becomes optimizable
    Let callee_cost be proc calculate_inline_cost with callee_ptr, context_ptr
    Let optimization_benefit be callee_cost divided by 5

    Note: Total benefit
    Let total_benefit be call_overhead plus optimization_benefit

    Return total_benefit
End Process

@Reasoning
This is the gate that converts an analyzed candidate into an actual
transformation. Four guards must pass simultaneously: an absolute cost
ceiling (500 units) so a single huge inline cannot inflate the caller
beyond reason, a minimum net-benefit floor (5 units) so we never burn
optimizer time on marginal wins, a recursion-depth check tied to the
context's max_inlining_depth, and the can_inline eligibility bit set
during candidate creation.

Hierarchical gating (cheapest checks first) is intentional: cost and
benefit are already memoized on the candidate so the early returns are
O(1), keeping this hot procedure trivial in the common reject case.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Determines if a call site is profitable to inline based on cost-benefit analysis.

Decision criteria:
1. Net benefit must be positive (benefit > cost)
2. Cost must be below absolute threshold (prevents huge inlines)
3. Not in recursive call chain (unless depth allows)
4. Callee is not too complex (exception handling, deep loops)

Thresholds:
- Maximum inline cost: 500 instruction units
- Minimum net benefit: 5 instruction units
- Maximum recursion depth: 4 levels

Returns 1 if should inline, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_profitable_to_inline" that takes candidate_ptr as Integer, context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If candidate_ptr is equal to 0 or context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get cost and benefit from candidate
    Let inline_cost be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 32
    Let call_overhead be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 40
    Let net_benefit be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 48

    Note: Check absolute cost threshold
    Let max_inline_cost be 500
    If inline_cost is greater than max_inline_cost:
        Return 0  Note: Too expensive to inline
    End If

    Note: Check net benefit threshold
    Let min_net_benefit be 5
    If net_benefit is less than min_net_benefit:
        Return 0  Note: Not profitable enough
    End If

    Note: Check recursion depth
    Let depth be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 64
    Let max_depth be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 88

    If depth is greater than or equal to max_depth:
        Return 0  Note: Too deep in recursion chain
    End If

    Note: Check if marked as eligible
    Let can_inline be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 72
    If can_inline is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Marked as ineligible for other reasons
    End If

    Note: All checks passed - profitable to inline
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: CALL SITE ANALYSIS
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
Resolves a MIR_CALL callee field to a MIRFunction pointer. Under the
canonical callee contract (task #461) a direct call carries the callee
FUNCTION-NAME STRING POINTER; defense in depth (mirroring the Wave 1
optimization.runa resolver) additionally tolerates two legacy forms:
(1) a value id whose defining instruction is a string MIR_CONST naming
the callee, and (2) a MIRFunction pointer stored directly. Resolution is
keyed on the MIRProgram functions list per OD-4 (function identity is
the MIRFunction POINTER; the name string only matters at boundaries).
An unresolvable callee is simply not inlinable — the call site is kept
but never becomes a candidate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. If the callee field's value id has a defining instruction in the
   caller that is a string MIR_CONST, capture its string payload as a
   candidate name (legacy form 1).
2. Walk the program's functions list. A function matches when:
   a. the function pointer equals the callee field (legacy form 2), or
   b. the function's interned name pointer equals the callee field
      (canonical form, pointer-interned names), or
   c. the function's name string content equals the callee field
      treated as a name string (canonical form, non-interned), or
   d. the function's name string content equals the captured
      string-CONST payload (legacy form 1).
Returns the resolved MIRFunction pointer or 0.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
The callee field is never dereferenced except (a) through
lookup_defining_instruction keyed by value id (a Dictionary probe, safe
for any integer) and (b) via string_equals against interned function
names — reached only when the field is a genuine string pointer per the
producer contract. Null program or caller degrade to pointer/name-less
matching, returning 0 rather than guessing.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "resolve_callee_function" that takes callee_field as Integer, caller_fn as Integer, program_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If callee_field is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If program_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Legacy form 1: value id defined by a string MIR_CONST
    Let const_name be 0
    If caller_fn is not equal to 0:
        Let callee_def be proc lookup_defining_instruction from MIR with caller_fn, callee_field
        If callee_def is not equal to 0:
            Let def_opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with callee_def
            If def_opcode is equal to 20001:
                Let def_is_string be proc is_const_string from MIRNodes with callee_def
                If def_is_string is equal to 1:
                    Set const_name to proc get_const_string from MIRNodes with callee_def
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Let functions be proc get_program_functions from MIRNodes with program_ptr
    If functions is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let func_count be proc length from List with functions
    Let resolved be 0
    Let scan be 0
    While scan is less than func_count:
        Let candidate be proc get from List with functions, scan
        If candidate is not equal to 0:
            If candidate is equal to callee_field:
                Set resolved to candidate
                Set scan to func_count
            Otherwise:
                Let candidate_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate, 0
                If candidate_name is not equal to 0:
                    If candidate_name is equal to callee_field:
                        Set resolved to candidate
                        Set scan to func_count
                    Otherwise:
                        If const_name is not equal to 0:
                            Let const_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with candidate_name, const_name
                            If const_match is equal to 1:
                                Set resolved to candidate
                                Set scan to func_count
                            End If
                        End If
                        If resolved is equal to 0:
                            Note: Canonical form: callee field is the name
                            Note: string pointer. Content comparison is only
                            Note: attempted when the field is plausibly a
                            Note: heap pointer (above the 64 KiB unmapped
                            Note: low region) so a legacy bare value id is
                            Note: never dereferenced as a string.
                            If callee_field is greater than 65536:
                                Let name_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with candidate_name, callee_field
                                If name_match is equal to 1:
                                    Set resolved to candidate
                                    Set scan to func_count
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set scan to scan plus 1
    End While

    Return resolved
End Process

@Reasoning
Call site analysis identifies all function calls in the current function
and creates candidate structures for potential inlining.

We collect information about each call site including:
- Callee function pointer
- Arguments and parameter mapping
- Execution frequency (hot vs cold)
- Surrounding context

This analysis phase separates identification from transformation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Scans all basic blocks and identifies function call instructions.

Algorithm:
1. Iterate through all basic blocks
2. Examine all instructions looking for MIR_CALL
3. Extract callee and argument information
4. Create CallSite structure for each call
5. Add to call_sites list in context

Returns number of call sites found.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_call_sites" that takes context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let call_sites be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 64
    Let current_func be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 24
    Let program_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8
    Let site_count be 0

    Note: Get block POINTERS from the canonical CFG storage list
    Let blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from CFG with cfg_ptr
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let block_count be proc length from List with blocks
    Let block_idx be 0

    While block_idx is less than block_count:
        Let block_ptr be proc get from List with blocks, block_idx

        If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Note: Get instructions in this block
            Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block_ptr
            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                Let inst_count be proc length from List with instructions
                Let inst_idx be 0

                While inst_idx is less than inst_count:
                    Let inst_ptr be proc get from List with instructions, inst_idx

                    If inst_ptr is not equal to 0:
                        Let opcode be proc get_opcode from MIRNodes with inst_ptr

                        Note: Check for direct call (MIR_CALL = 20304)
                        If opcode is equal to 20304:
                            Note: Create CallSite structure
                            Let site_size be 64
                            Let site_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with site_size

                            If site_ptr is not equal to 0:
                                Note: Set call_instruction_ptr
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 0, inst_ptr

                                Note: Set call_block_ptr
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 8, block_ptr

                                Note: Resolve the canonical callee field
                                Note: (MIRCall ext offset 80: name string
                                Note: pointer per task #461) to a MIRFunction
                                Note: pointer via the program functions list
                                Let callee_field be proc get_call_callee from MIRNodes with inst_ptr
                                Let callee_fn be proc resolve_callee_function with callee_field, current_func, program_ptr
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 16, callee_fn

                                Note: Argument count from the canonical
                                Note: MIRCall record (ext offset 96)
                                Let arg_count be proc get_call_argument_count from MIRNodes with inst_ptr
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 24, arg_count

                                Note: Set is_indirect to false (this is direct call)
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 32, 0

                                Note: Estimate call frequency (use loop depth as proxy)
                                Let loop_depth be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block_ptr, 72
                                Let frequency be 1
                                If loop_depth is greater than 0:
                                    Set frequency to 10  Note: In loop, likely hot
                                End If
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 40, frequency

                                Note: Continuation block is materialized by
                                Note: perform_inline_transformation (it splits
                                Note: the call block); record the current
                                Note: fallthrough successor for analysis only.
                                Let continuation be 0
                                Let successors be proc get_block_successors from MIR with block_ptr
                                If successors is not equal to 0:
                                    Let succ_count be proc length from List with successors
                                    If succ_count is greater than 0:
                                        Note: Successor lists hold BLOCK IDS
                                        Let succ_id be proc get from List with successors, 0
                                        Set continuation to proc get_block_by_id from CFG with cfg_ptr, succ_id
                                    End If
                                End If
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 48, continuation

                                Note: Mark as not yet analyzed
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 56, 0

                                Note: Add to call sites list
                                proc append from List with call_sites, site_ptr
                                Set site_count to site_count plus 1
                            End If
                        End If

                        Note: Check for indirect call (MIR_CALL_INDIRECT = 20305)
                        If opcode is equal to 20305:
                            Note: Create CallSite structure for indirect call
                            Set site_size to 64
                            Set site_ptr to proc allocate from Layout with site_size

                            If site_ptr is not equal to 0:
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 0, inst_ptr
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 8, block_ptr
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 16, 0  Note: Unknown callee
                                Let ind_arg_count be proc get_call_argument_count from MIRNodes with inst_ptr
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 24, ind_arg_count
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 32, 1  Note: is_indirect
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 40, 1
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 48, 0
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 56, 0

                                proc append from List with call_sites, site_ptr
                                Set site_count to site_count plus 1
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set inst_idx to inst_idx plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Note: Update blocks_processed counter
            Let blocks_processed be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 104
            Set blocks_processed to blocks_processed plus 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 104, blocks_processed
        End If

        Set block_idx to block_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: Update total_calls_analyzed counter
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 48, site_count

    Return site_count
End Process

@Reasoning
Candidate creation is the second analysis pass. The first pass (collect_call_sites)
walks the CFG once and records every call instruction; this pass walks the
shorter call-site list and attaches cost-benefit data to each direct call.
Splitting the work this way means cost analysis runs exactly once per call
site even when the cost computation itself is heavyweight, and the cost_cache
on the context dedupes work across multiple call sites to the same callee.

Direct self-recursion (callee equals current_func) is filtered out here by
clearing can_inline, rather than later in the profitability check. This
prevents the depth counter from incrementing for an inline that we already
know will be rejected, keeping the depth limit reserved for legitimate
multi-level non-recursive inlining chains.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Creates inline candidates from call sites by performing cost-benefit analysis.

Algorithm:
1. Iterate through all call sites
2. Skip indirect calls (cannot inline)
3. Calculate inline cost for callee
4. Calculate benefit of inlining
5. Compute net benefit
6. Create InlineCandidate structure
7. Add to candidates list

Returns number of candidates created.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_inline_candidates" that takes context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let call_sites be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 64
    Let candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 56
    Let current_func be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 24

    Let site_count be proc length from List with call_sites
    Let candidate_count be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than site_count:
        Let site_ptr be proc get from List with call_sites, i

        If site_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Note: Skip indirect calls
            Let is_indirect be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 32
            If is_indirect is equal to 0:
                Let call_inst be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 0
                Let call_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 8
                Let callee be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with site_ptr, 16

                If callee is not equal to 0:
                    Note: Calculate costs
                    Let inline_cost be proc calculate_inline_cost with callee, context_ptr
                    Let benefit be proc calculate_inline_benefit with callee, call_inst, context_ptr
                    Let net_benefit be benefit minus inline_cost

                    Note: Check if recursive
                    Let is_recursive be 0
                    If callee is equal to current_func:
                        Set is_recursive to 1
                    End If

                    Note: Create candidate structure
                    Let candidate_size be 80
                    Let candidate_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with candidate_size

                    If candidate_ptr is not equal to 0:
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 0, call_inst
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 8, call_block
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 16, callee
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 24, current_func
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 32, inline_cost
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 40, benefit
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 48, net_benefit
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 56, is_recursive

                        Note: Get current inlining depth
                        Let depth be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 80
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 64, depth

                        Note: Determine if can inline (preliminary check)
                        Let can_inline be 1
                        If inline_cost is greater than 500:
                            Set can_inline to 0  Note: Cost exceeds maximum threshold
                        End If
                        If is_recursive is equal to 1:
                            Set can_inline to 0  Note: Direct self-recursion rejected (non-recursive nested inlining uses depth limit)
                        End If
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 72, can_inline

                        proc append from List with candidates, candidate_ptr
                        Set candidate_count to candidate_count plus 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return candidate_count
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: FUNCTION BODY CLONING
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
Function body cloning is the core operation for inlining. We must:
1. Clone all basic blocks and instructions from callee
2. Remap SSA value IDs (callee values to fresh values in the caller)
3. Substitute parameters with argument values
4. Remap intra-body block targets (terminators and phi incoming blocks)
   to the freshly allocated caller block IDs and recreate the callee's
   internal CFG edges between the clones

Instruction copies go through MIR.clone_instruction (OD-6): under the
OD-1 prefix-embedded representation extended records are 72-144 bytes
with opcode-specific payloads and embedded Lists, so any header-only or
fixed-size copy is a heap overrun and an aliasing bug. clone_instruction
sizes the copy from the canonical opcode-band table and deep-copies the
embedded Lists (phi pairs, call arguments, switch cases, landing-pad
clauses).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns a clone rig List on success, 0 on failure:
  index 0: List of cloned block pointers (callee storage order)
  index 1: clone of the callee's ENTRY block (jump target for the call
           block after the split)
  index 2: OMap old callee block id -> new caller block id (caller
           destroys it after target rewriting completes)

Passes:
  1. Reset the context value_remap OMap, then bind parameters: the i-th
     entry of the callee's parameter value-id List (MIRFunction offset
     16) maps to the i-th entry of the call's argument List (MIRCall
     ext offset 88).
  2. Create one fresh block per callee block (MIR.allocate_block_id on
     the CALLER cfg), publish it via MIR.add_block_to_cfg, and record
     the id mapping.
  3. Clone every instruction via MIR.clone_instruction; allocate a
     fresh SSA id for every value-producing clone (header value_id and
     the ext result mirror at 72 via set_instruction_result_id),
     register it in the caller's value_to_instruction map, record the
     old-to-new mapping, and append the clone through the canonical
     CFG.add_instruction_to_block (stamps parent_block). Phi clones are
     additionally registered in the clone block's phi registry (offset
     88).
  4. remap_cloned_values rewrites every value USE in the clones from
     the remap table; rewrite_clone_block_targets rewrites every block
     TARGET from the id map; internal CFG edges are recreated through
     MIR.add_cfg_edge using the mapped ids.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Allocates one MIR basic block and one sized record copy per source block
and instruction, so memory pressure scales linearly with callee size.
The remap table is an integer-keyed ordered map: O(1) hash inserts and
probes with deterministic insertion-order iteration; resetting it per
inline keeps stale mappings from a previous candidate out of scope.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The function verifies callee_cfg before walking it, so a callee with a
NULL CFG (typically an external or unimplemented function) cannot
trigger a wild pointer dereference. All clone writes target freshly
allocated records; the callee's blocks and instructions are read-only
throughout, so a mid-clone failure cannot corrupt the callee. The rig
and its id map are owned by the caller (perform_inline_transformation
destroys them after wiring).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "set_instruction_result_id" that takes inst_ptr as Integer, new_value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Coherent RESULT-id rewrite for prefix-embedded records (OD-1):
    Note: value-producing extended records duplicate the result id at ext
    Note: offset 72, so a header-only write desynchronizes every extended
    Note: payload reader. Phi nodes route through the canonical
    Note: set_phi_result_value_id which maintains both views.
    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst_ptr

    If opcode is equal to 20300:
        Return proc set_phi_result_value_id from MIRNodes with inst_ptr, new_value_id
    End If

    proc set_mir_node_value_id from MIR with inst_ptr, new_value_id

    Note: Ext result mirror at offset 72 per the as-built Part 1.1 table:
    Note: CONST, arithmetic/bitwise band (minus plain-header COPY 20008),
    Note: comparisons, LOAD, ALLOCA, CALL/CALL_INDIRECT, casts, atomics,
    Note: vector band, INVOKE, LANDINGPAD. Plain-header value producers
    Note: (COPY, LOAD_FIELD, ADDRESS_OF, DEREF) carry the id only at
    Note: header offset 8.
    Let has_ext_result be 0
    If opcode is equal to 20001:
        Set has_ext_result to 1
    End If
    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20002 and opcode is less than or equal to 20007:
        Set has_ext_result to 1
    End If
    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20010 and opcode is less than or equal to 20016:
        Set has_ext_result to 1
    End If
    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20100 and opcode is less than or equal to 20105:
        Set has_ext_result to 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20200:
        Set has_ext_result to 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20202:
        Set has_ext_result to 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20304 or opcode is equal to 20305:
        Set has_ext_result to 1
    End If
    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20400 and opcode is less than or equal to 20408:
        Set has_ext_result to 1
    End If
    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20500 and opcode is less than or equal to 20510:
        Set has_ext_result to 1
    End If
    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20600 and opcode is less than or equal to 20622:
        Set has_ext_result to 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20700 or opcode is equal to 20701:
        Set has_ext_result to 1
    End If

    If has_ext_result is equal to 1:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 72, new_value_id
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "rewrite_clone_block_targets" that takes inst_ptr as Integer, block_id_map as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Rewrites every BLOCK-ID payload of a cloned instruction from the
    Note: old callee block numbering to the fresh caller numbering. Block
    Note: ids live ONLY in the extended region (never in header operand
    Note: slots) per OD-1: JUMP target at 72; BRANCH true/false at 80/88;
    Note: SWITCH case pairs (value at 2N, block at 2N+1) at 80 plus the
    Note: default at 96; INVOKE normal/exception at 112/120; LANDINGPAD
    Note: cleanup at 104; PHI incoming pairs (block at 2N, value at 2N+1)
    Note: at 80.
    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If block_id_map is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst_ptr

    If opcode is equal to 20302:
        Let jump_target be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 72
        Let jump_mapped be proc omap_contains from OMap with block_id_map, jump_target
        If jump_mapped is equal to 1:
            Let new_jump_target be proc omap_get from OMap with block_id_map, jump_target
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 72, new_jump_target
        End If
        Return 1
    End If

    If opcode is equal to 20301:
        Let true_target be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 80
        Let true_mapped be proc omap_contains from OMap with block_id_map, true_target
        If true_mapped is equal to 1:
            Let new_true be proc omap_get from OMap with block_id_map, true_target
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 80, new_true
        End If
        Let false_target be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 88
        Let false_mapped be proc omap_contains from OMap with block_id_map, false_target
        If false_mapped is equal to 1:
            Let new_false be proc omap_get from OMap with block_id_map, false_target
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 88, new_false
        End If
        Return 1
    End If

    If opcode is equal to 20306:
        Let cases be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 80
        If cases is not equal to 0:
            Let case_len be proc length from List with cases
            Let case_idx be 1
            While case_idx is less than case_len:
                Let case_block be proc get from List with cases, case_idx
                Let case_mapped be proc omap_contains from OMap with block_id_map, case_block
                If case_mapped is equal to 1:
                    Let new_case_block be proc omap_get from OMap with block_id_map, case_block
                    proc set from List with cases, case_idx, new_case_block
                End If
                Set case_idx to case_idx plus 2
            End While
        End If
        Let default_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 96
        Let default_mapped be proc omap_contains from OMap with block_id_map, default_block
        If default_mapped is equal to 1:
            Let new_default be proc omap_get from OMap with block_id_map, default_block
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 96, new_default
        End If
        Return 1
    End If

    If opcode is equal to 20700:
        Let normal_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 112
        Let normal_mapped be proc omap_contains from OMap with block_id_map, normal_block
        If normal_mapped is equal to 1:
            Let new_normal be proc omap_get from OMap with block_id_map, normal_block
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 112, new_normal
        End If
        Let exc_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 120
        Let exc_mapped be proc omap_contains from OMap with block_id_map, exc_block
        If exc_mapped is equal to 1:
            Let new_exc be proc omap_get from OMap with block_id_map, exc_block
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 120, new_exc
        End If
        Return 1
    End If

    If opcode is equal to 20701:
        Let cleanup_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 104
        Let cleanup_mapped be proc omap_contains from OMap with block_id_map, cleanup_block
        If cleanup_mapped is equal to 1:
            Let new_cleanup be proc omap_get from OMap with block_id_map, cleanup_block
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 104, new_cleanup
        End If
        Return 1
    End If

    If opcode is equal to 20300:
        Let pairs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 80
        If pairs is not equal to 0:
            Let pair_len be proc length from List with pairs
            Let pair_idx be 0
            While pair_idx is less than pair_len:
                Let incoming_block be proc get from List with pairs, pair_idx
                Let inc_mapped be proc omap_contains from OMap with block_id_map, incoming_block
                If inc_mapped is equal to 1:
                    Let new_incoming be proc omap_get from OMap with block_id_map, incoming_block
                    proc set from List with pairs, pair_idx, new_incoming
                End If
                Set pair_idx to pair_idx plus 2
            End While
        End If
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "clone_function_body" that takes callee_ptr as Integer, call_inst_ptr as Integer, context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If callee_ptr is equal to 0 or context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If call_inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get callee CFG
    Let callee_cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_ptr, 8
    If callee_cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Reset the value remap (integer-keyed ordered map)
    Let value_remap be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72
    If value_remap is not equal to 0:
        proc omap_destroy from OMap with value_remap
    End If
    Set value_remap to proc omap_create from OMap
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72, value_remap

    Note: Get caller CFG and function
    Let caller_cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let caller_func be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 24

    Note: Pass 1 - bind parameters to call arguments. The callee parameter
    Note: List (MIRFunction offset 16) holds parameter VALUE IDS; the call
    Note: argument List (MIRCall ext offset 88) holds argument VALUE IDS.
    Let params be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_ptr, 16
    Let param_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_ptr, 24
    Let args be proc get_call_arguments from MIRNodes with call_inst_ptr
    Let arg_count be proc get_call_argument_count from MIRNodes with call_inst_ptr

    Let bind_count be param_count
    If arg_count is less than bind_count:
        Set bind_count to arg_count
    End If

    If params is not equal to 0 and args is not equal to 0:
        Let bind_idx be 0
        While bind_idx is less than bind_count:
            Let param_vid be proc get from List with params, bind_idx
            Let arg_vid be proc get from List with args, bind_idx
            If param_vid is not equal to 0:
                proc omap_set from OMap with value_remap, param_vid, arg_vid
            End If
            Set bind_idx to bind_idx plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Pass 2 - create one fresh caller block per callee block
    Let callee_blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from CFG with callee_cfg
    If callee_blocks is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let block_count be proc length from List with callee_blocks

    Let cloned_blocks be proc create from List
    Let block_id_map be proc omap_create from OMap

    Let callee_entry be proc get_cfg_entry_block from MIR with callee_cfg
    Let entry_clone be 0

    Let block_idx be 0
    While block_idx is less than block_count:
        Let orig_block_ptr be proc get from List with callee_blocks, block_idx

        If orig_block_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let orig_block_id be proc get_mir_basic_block_id from CFG with orig_block_ptr
            Let new_block_id be proc allocate_block_id from MIR with caller_cfg
            Let cloned_block be proc create_mir_basic_block from MIR with new_block_id, 0
            If cloned_block is equal to 0:
                proc destroy from List with cloned_blocks
                proc omap_destroy from OMap with block_id_map
                Return 0
            End If

            proc add_block_to_cfg from MIR with caller_cfg, cloned_block
            proc omap_set from OMap with block_id_map, orig_block_id, new_block_id
            proc append from List with cloned_blocks, cloned_block

            If orig_block_ptr is equal to callee_entry:
                Set entry_clone to cloned_block
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Note: Keep index correspondence between source and clone lists
            proc append from List with cloned_blocks, 0
        End If

        Set block_idx to block_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: First clone is the entry when the callee never set entry_block
    If entry_clone is equal to 0:
        Let clone_total be proc length from List with cloned_blocks
        If clone_total is greater than 0:
            Set entry_clone to proc get from List with cloned_blocks, 0
        End If
    End If

    Note: Pass 3 - clone instructions via the canonical OD-6 deep copier
    Set block_idx to 0
    While block_idx is less than block_count:
        Let src_block be proc get from List with callee_blocks, block_idx
        Let dst_block be proc get from List with cloned_blocks, block_idx

        If src_block is not equal to 0 and dst_block is not equal to 0:
            Let orig_instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with src_block
            Let inst_count be proc length from List with orig_instructions
            Let inst_idx be 0

            While inst_idx is less than inst_count:
                Let orig_inst be proc get from List with orig_instructions, inst_idx

                If orig_inst is not equal to 0:
                    Let cloned_inst be proc clone_instruction from MIR with orig_inst
                    If cloned_inst is not equal to 0:
                        Note: Fresh SSA id for value-producing clones
                        Let orig_value_id be proc get_mir_node_value_id from MIR with orig_inst
                        If orig_value_id is not equal to 0:
                            Let new_value_id be proc allocate_value_id from MIR with caller_func
                            proc set_instruction_result_id with cloned_inst, new_value_id
                            proc omap_set from OMap with value_remap, orig_value_id, new_value_id
                            proc register_value_definition from MIR with caller_func, new_value_id, cloned_inst
                        End If

                        Note: Canonical append (stamps parent_block, count)
                        proc add_instruction_to_block from CFG with dst_block, cloned_inst

                        Note: Maintain the block phi registry for phi clones
                        Let clone_opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with cloned_inst
                        If clone_opcode is equal to 20300:
                            Let phi_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dst_block, 88
                            If phi_registry is not equal to 0:
                                proc append from List with phi_registry, cloned_inst
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If

                Set inst_idx to inst_idx plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Set block_idx to block_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: Pass 4 - rewrite value uses and block targets in every clone
    proc remap_cloned_values with cloned_blocks, context_ptr

    Set block_idx to 0
    While block_idx is less than block_count:
        Let target_block be proc get from List with cloned_blocks, block_idx
        If target_block is not equal to 0:
            Let target_insts be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with target_block
            Let target_count be proc length from List with target_insts
            Let t_idx be 0
            While t_idx is less than target_count:
                Let t_inst be proc get from List with target_insts, t_idx
                If t_inst is not equal to 0:
                    proc rewrite_clone_block_targets with t_inst, block_id_map
                End If
                Set t_idx to t_idx plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set block_idx to block_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: Pass 5 - recreate the callee's internal CFG edges between clones
    Set block_idx to 0
    While block_idx is less than block_count:
        Let edge_src be proc get from List with callee_blocks, block_idx
        If edge_src is not equal to 0:
            Let src_old_id be proc get_mir_basic_block_id from CFG with edge_src
            Let src_new_id be proc omap_get from OMap with block_id_map, src_old_id
            Let src_succs be proc get_block_successors from MIR with edge_src
            If src_succs is not equal to 0:
                Let succ_count be proc length from List with src_succs
                Let s_idx be 0
                While s_idx is less than succ_count:
                    Let old_succ_id be proc get from List with src_succs, s_idx
                    Let succ_known be proc omap_contains from OMap with block_id_map, old_succ_id
                    If succ_known is equal to 1:
                        Let new_succ_id be proc omap_get from OMap with block_id_map, old_succ_id
                        proc add_cfg_edge from MIR with caller_cfg, src_new_id, new_succ_id
                    End If
                    Set s_idx to s_idx plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
        Set block_idx to block_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: Package the clone rig
    Let rig be proc create from List
    proc append from List with rig, cloned_blocks
    proc append from List with rig, entry_clone
    proc append from List with rig, block_id_map

    Return rig
End Process

@Reasoning
Cloning preserves the textual shape of the callee but leaves operands
pointing at the callee's SSA value IDs. SSA correctness in the caller
requires every use to reach a definition that dominates it; after
inlining, only the remapped value IDs satisfy that property. Performing
this pass after cloning (rather than during) lets clone_function_body
remain a pure structural copy and isolates the remap logic, which is the
only step that depends on the populated value_remap table.

A missing entry in the remap dictionary (lookup returns 0) is treated as
"already in caller scope" and the operand is left alone. This is the
correct behavior for arguments that were substituted directly during
parameter binding and for constants that don't carry value IDs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Remaps SSA values in cloned instructions using the value remap dictionary.

After cloning, all operands still reference the original callee's value IDs.
This function updates them to reference the new cloned value IDs.

Algorithm:
1. Iterate through all cloned instructions
2. For each operand, look up remapped value ID
3. Replace operand with remapped ID
4. Handle special cases (phi nodes, branches)

Returns 1 on success.
@End Implementation

Process called "remap_cloned_values" that takes cloned_blocks as Integer, context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If cloned_blocks is equal to 0 or context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value_remap be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72
    Let block_count be proc length from List with cloned_blocks
    Let block_idx be 0

    While block_idx is less than block_count:
        Let block_ptr be proc get from List with cloned_blocks, block_idx

        If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block_ptr
            Let inst_count be proc length from List with instructions
            Let inst_idx be 0

            While inst_idx is less than inst_count:
                Let inst_ptr be proc get from List with instructions, inst_idx

                If inst_ptr is not equal to 0:
                    Note: Header operand slots 1-3 rewritten through the
                    Note: canonical use mutator so the OD-1 ext mirrors
                    Note: (binop left/right, load address, store address/
                    Note: value, branch condition, return value, ...) stay
                    Note: coherent with the header.
                    Let slot be 1
                    While slot is less than 4:
                        Let operand be proc get_mir_node_operand from MIR with inst_ptr, slot
                        If operand is not equal to 0:
                            Let known be proc omap_contains from OMap with value_remap, operand
                            If known is equal to 1:
                                Let remapped be proc omap_get from OMap with value_remap, operand
                                proc set_mir_node_used_value from MIRNodes with inst_ptr, slot, remapped
                            End If
                        End If
                        Set slot to slot plus 1
                    End While

                    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst_ptr

                    Note: Phi incoming VALUES (pairs: block at 2N, value at
                    Note: 2N+1) — header operands are zero for phis
                    If opcode is equal to 20300:
                        Let incoming_count be proc get_phi_incoming_count from MIRNodes with inst_ptr
                        Let inc_idx be 0
                        While inc_idx is less than incoming_count:
                            Let inc_value be proc get_phi_incoming_value from MIRNodes with inst_ptr, inc_idx
                            If inc_value is not equal to 0:
                                Let inc_known be proc omap_contains from OMap with value_remap, inc_value
                                If inc_known is equal to 1:
                                    Let inc_remapped be proc omap_get from OMap with value_remap, inc_value
                                    proc set_phi_incoming_value from MIRNodes with inst_ptr, inc_idx, inc_remapped
                                End If
                            End If
                            Set inc_idx to inc_idx plus 1
                        End While
                    End If

                    Note: Call / invoke argument lists hold value-id USES
                    If opcode is equal to 20304 or opcode is equal to 20305 or opcode is equal to 20700:
                        Note: An INDIRECT callee (ext offset 80) is itself a
                        Note: value-id use and must be remapped; a direct
                        Note: callee is a name string pointer and is left
                        Note: alone (it can never collide with a small id
                        Note: present in the remap table).
                        If opcode is equal to 20305:
                            Let ind_callee be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 80
                            If ind_callee is not equal to 0:
                                Let callee_known be proc omap_contains from OMap with value_remap, ind_callee
                                If callee_known is equal to 1:
                                    Let callee_remapped be proc omap_get from OMap with value_remap, ind_callee
                                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 80, callee_remapped
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                        Let call_args be proc get_call_arguments from MIRNodes with inst_ptr
                        If call_args is not equal to 0:
                            Let call_arg_count be proc length from List with call_args
                            Let a_idx be 0
                            While a_idx is less than call_arg_count:
                                Let arg_use be proc get from List with call_args, a_idx
                                If arg_use is not equal to 0:
                                    Let arg_known be proc omap_contains from OMap with value_remap, arg_use
                                    If arg_known is equal to 1:
                                        Let arg_remapped be proc omap_get from OMap with value_remap, arg_use
                                        proc set from List with call_args, a_idx, arg_remapped
                                    End If
                                End If
                                Set a_idx to a_idx plus 1
                            End While
                        End If
                    End If
                End If

                Set inst_idx to inst_idx plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Set block_idx to block_idx plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: INLINING TRANSFORMATION
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
The inlining transformation integrates the cloned callee body into the caller.

Steps:
1. Split the call block at the call instruction
2. Wire cloned entry to split point
3. Wire cloned exits to continuation block
4. Remove the call instruction
5. Update CFG edges
6. Recompute SSA form

This maintains CFG integrity and SSA correctness.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Performs the actual inlining transformation for a candidate.

Algorithm:
1. Verify the call instruction (opcode MIR_CALL 20304) and locate it in
   its claimed block — both BEFORE any mutation.
2. clone_function_body: blocks, instructions (OD-6 clones with fresh
   SSA ids), parameter binding, use remap, target remap, internal edges.
3. Split the call block: instructions after the call (including its
   terminator) move to a fresh continuation block; the call block's
   successor edges are transferred to the continuation (edge lists,
   cached counts, edge table via the canonical remove_cfg_edge /
   add_cfg_edge, phi predecessors via update_phi_predecessor).
4. Terminate the call block with a jump to the cloned entry block.
5. Rewrite every cloned MIR_RETURN (20303) into a MIR_JUMP (20302) to
   the continuation, collecting (returning block id, return value id)
   pairs.
6. Substitute the call result: one returning path replaces uses
   directly; multiple returning paths materialize a phi at the head of
   the continuation merging the per-path return values.
7. Invalidate the caller CFG's dominance_computed flag (offset 56) —
   the topology changed; downstream passes recompute on demand. SSA
   form is preserved structurally (fresh ids, dominating definitions,
   merge phi), so no SSA reconstruction is required here.

Returns 1 on success, 0 on failure.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
The CFG mutation phase (split call block, wire continuation edges,
rewrite returns into jumps) is O(I_callee) for the return-rewrite scan
and O(1) per CFG-edge update. The call-result use replacement is one
O(I_caller) walk. Dominance recomputation is deferred to the next
consumer rather than triggered eagerly per inline.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The opcode of the call instruction is verified to be MIR_CALL (20304)
and the call is located in its claimed block BEFORE the clone phase, so
a corrupted candidate is rejected without mutating any state. The clone
rig and block-id map are always destroyed before return on the success
path; the callee function is never written to.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "replace_value_uses_in_cfg" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer, old_value_id as Integer, new_value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Rewrites every USE of old_value_id across the whole CFG to
    Note: new_value_id: header operand slots (with their OD-1 ext
    Note: mirrors via set_mir_node_used_value), phi incoming values, and
    Note: call/invoke argument lists. MIR.replace_all_uses is unusable
    Note: here because it walks MIRValue use-lists that SSA never
    Note: materializes (Wave 4 finding) — an explicit walk is the
    Note: canonical pattern (mirrors ssa.runa eliminate_trivial_phi_nodes).
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If old_value_id is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from CFG with cfg_ptr
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let block_count be proc length from List with blocks
    Let b_idx be 0
    While b_idx is less than block_count:
        Let block_ptr be proc get from List with blocks, b_idx
        If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block_ptr
            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                Let inst_count be proc length from List with instructions
                Let i_idx be 0
                While i_idx is less than inst_count:
                    Let inst_ptr be proc get from List with instructions, i_idx
                    If inst_ptr is not equal to 0:
                        Let slot be 1
                        While slot is less than 4:
                            Let operand be proc get_mir_node_operand from MIR with inst_ptr, slot
                            If operand is equal to old_value_id:
                                proc set_mir_node_used_value from MIRNodes with inst_ptr, slot, new_value_id
                            End If
                            Set slot to slot plus 1
                        End While

                        Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst_ptr

                        If opcode is equal to 20300:
                            Let incoming_count be proc get_phi_incoming_count from MIRNodes with inst_ptr
                            Let inc_idx be 0
                            While inc_idx is less than incoming_count:
                                Let inc_value be proc get_phi_incoming_value from MIRNodes with inst_ptr, inc_idx
                                If inc_value is equal to old_value_id:
                                    proc set_phi_incoming_value from MIRNodes with inst_ptr, inc_idx, new_value_id
                                End If
                                Set inc_idx to inc_idx plus 1
                            End While
                        End If

                        If opcode is equal to 20304 or opcode is equal to 20305 or opcode is equal to 20700:
                            If opcode is equal to 20305:
                                Let ind_callee be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 80
                                If ind_callee is equal to old_value_id:
                                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 80, new_value_id
                                End If
                            End If
                            Let call_args be proc get_call_arguments from MIRNodes with inst_ptr
                            If call_args is not equal to 0:
                                Let call_arg_count be proc length from List with call_args
                                Let a_idx be 0
                                While a_idx is less than call_arg_count:
                                    Let arg_use be proc get from List with call_args, a_idx
                                    If arg_use is equal to old_value_id:
                                        proc set from List with call_args, a_idx, new_value_id
                                    End If
                                    Set a_idx to a_idx plus 1
                                End While
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set i_idx to i_idx plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
        Set b_idx to b_idx plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "perform_inline_transformation" that takes candidate_ptr as Integer, context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If candidate_ptr is equal to 0 or context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let call_inst_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 0
    Let call_block_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 8
    Let callee_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate_ptr, 16

    If call_inst_ptr is equal to 0 or call_block_ptr is equal to 0 or callee_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Verify the call BEFORE any mutation
    Let call_opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with call_inst_ptr
    If call_opcode is not equal to 20304:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let caller_func be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 24

    Note: Locate the call in its claimed block BEFORE cloning
    Let call_block_insts be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with call_block_ptr
    If call_block_insts is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let call_inst_idx be proc list_index_of from List with call_block_insts, call_inst_ptr
    If call_inst_idx is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Clone the callee body (blocks, values, parameters, targets, edges)
    Let rig be proc clone_function_body with callee_ptr, call_inst_ptr, context_ptr
    If rig is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cloned_blocks be proc get from List with rig, 0
    Let entry_block_ptr be proc get from List with rig, 1
    Let block_id_map be proc get from List with rig, 2

    If entry_block_ptr is equal to 0:
        proc omap_destroy from OMap with block_id_map
        proc destroy from List with cloned_blocks
        proc destroy from List with rig
        Return 0
    End If

    Let call_block_id be proc get_mir_basic_block_id from CFG with call_block_ptr
    Let entry_block_id be proc get_mir_basic_block_id from CFG with entry_block_ptr

    Note: Create the continuation block and publish it
    Let continuation_block be proc create_basic_block from CFG with cfg
    If continuation_block is equal to 0:
        proc omap_destroy from OMap with block_id_map
        proc destroy from List with cloned_blocks
        proc destroy from List with rig
        Return 0
    End If
    proc add_block_to_function from CFG with cfg, continuation_block
    Let continuation_id be proc get_mir_basic_block_id from CFG with continuation_block

    Note: Move the instructions AFTER the call (including the original
    Note: terminator) into the continuation, then drop the tail of the
    Note: call block's list (call instruction included).
    Let inst_count be proc length from List with call_block_insts
    Let move_idx be call_inst_idx plus 1
    While move_idx is less than inst_count:
        Let inst_to_move be proc get from List with call_block_insts, move_idx
        proc add_instruction_to_block from CFG with continuation_block, inst_to_move
        Set move_idx to move_idx plus 1
    End While

    While proc length from List with call_block_insts is greater than call_inst_idx:
        Let tail_len be proc length from List with call_block_insts
        proc list_remove from List with call_block_insts, (tail_len minus 1)
    End While
    Let truncated_len be proc length from List with call_block_insts
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with call_block_ptr, 24, truncated_len

    Note: Transfer the call block's successor edges to the continuation.
    Note: Successor lists hold BLOCK IDS; copy them first because
    Note: remove_cfg_edge mutates the list being walked.
    Let old_succs be proc get_block_successors from MIR with call_block_ptr
    Let moved_succ_ids be proc create from List
    If old_succs is not equal to 0:
        Let old_succ_count be proc length from List with old_succs
        Let os_idx be 0
        While os_idx is less than old_succ_count:
            Let old_succ_id be proc get from List with old_succs, os_idx
            proc append from List with moved_succ_ids, old_succ_id
            Set os_idx to os_idx plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Let moved_count be proc length from List with moved_succ_ids
    Let ms_idx be 0
    While ms_idx is less than moved_count:
        Let succ_id be proc get from List with moved_succ_ids, ms_idx
        proc remove_cfg_edge from CFG with cfg, call_block_id, succ_id
        proc add_cfg_edge from MIR with cfg, continuation_id, succ_id
        proc update_phi_predecessor from CFG with cfg, succ_id, call_block_id, continuation_id
        Set ms_idx to ms_idx plus 1
    End While
    proc destroy from List with moved_succ_ids

    Note: Terminate the call block with a jump into the inlined body
    Let entry_jump be proc create_mir_jump from MIRNodes with entry_block_id
    proc add_instruction_to_block from CFG with call_block_ptr, entry_jump
    proc add_cfg_edge from MIR with cfg, call_block_id, entry_block_id

    Note: Rewrite cloned returns (MIR_RETURN 20303) into jumps to the
    Note: continuation (MIR_JUMP 20302 — fresh records, not in-place
    Note: opcode rewrites: an 88-byte return and an 80-byte jump are
    Note: different record shapes). Collect (block id, return value id).
    Let return_blocks be proc create from List
    Let return_values be proc create from List

    Let clone_count be proc length from List with cloned_blocks
    Let cb_idx be 0
    While cb_idx is less than clone_count:
        Let cloned_block be proc get from List with cloned_blocks, cb_idx
        If cloned_block is not equal to 0:
            Let block_insts be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with cloned_block
            Let block_inst_count be proc length from List with block_insts

            If block_inst_count is greater than 0:
                Let last_inst be proc get from List with block_insts, (block_inst_count minus 1)
                Let last_opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with last_inst

                If last_opcode is equal to 20303:
                    Note: Return value id (already remapped) at ext offset 72
                    Let ret_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with last_inst, 72
                    Let cloned_block_id be proc get_mir_basic_block_id from CFG with cloned_block

                    Let cont_jump be proc create_mir_jump from MIRNodes with continuation_id
                    proc set from List with block_insts, (block_inst_count minus 1), cont_jump
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cont_jump, 56, cloned_block

                    Note: The detached return clone is owned here - free it
                    proc deallocate from Layout with last_inst

                    proc add_cfg_edge from MIR with cfg, cloned_block_id, continuation_id

                    If ret_value is not equal to 0:
                        proc append from List with return_blocks, cloned_block_id
                        proc append from List with return_values, ret_value
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set cb_idx to cb_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: Substitute the call result with the inlined return value(s)
    Let call_result_id be proc get_mir_node_value_id from MIR with call_inst_ptr
    Let return_count be proc length from List with return_values

    If call_result_id is not equal to 0:
        If return_count is equal to 1:
            Let single_ret be proc get from List with return_values, 0
            proc replace_value_uses_in_cfg with cfg, call_result_id, single_ret
        End If
        If return_count is greater than 1:
            Note: Multiple returning paths merge in a continuation phi
            Let merge_vid be proc allocate_value_id from MIR with caller_func
            Let call_return_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_inst_ptr, 104
            Let merge_phi be proc create_mir_phi_node from MIRNodes with merge_vid, call_return_type, continuation_block

            Let r_idx be 0
            While r_idx is less than return_count:
                Let r_block be proc get from List with return_blocks, r_idx
                Let r_value be proc get from List with return_values, r_idx
                proc add_phi_incoming from MIRNodes with merge_phi, r_block, r_value
                Set r_idx to r_idx plus 1
            End While

            proc insert_instruction_at_block_start from MIR with continuation_block, merge_phi
            Let cont_phi_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with continuation_block, 88
            If cont_phi_registry is not equal to 0:
                proc append from List with cont_phi_registry, merge_phi
            End If
            proc register_value_definition from MIR with caller_func, merge_vid, merge_phi

            proc replace_value_uses_in_cfg with cfg, call_result_id, merge_vid
        End If
    End If

    proc destroy from List with return_blocks
    proc destroy from List with return_values

    Note: Topology changed - invalidate cached dominance (MIRCFG offset 56)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 56, 0

    Note: Release the clone rig (blocks now owned by the caller CFG)
    proc omap_destroy from OMap with block_id_map
    proc destroy from List with cloned_blocks
    proc destroy from List with rig

    Note: Increment inlined calls counter
    Let inlined_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 32, (inlined_count plus 1)

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: MAIN ENTRY POINTS
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
This is the master orchestrator for inlining a single function. The
pipeline is intentionally three-phase: analyze (collect_call_sites),
score (create_inline_candidates), and transform (perform_inline_transformation
gated by is_profitable_to_inline). Separating analysis from transformation
is essential because the transformation phase mutates the caller's CFG; if
we interleaved them, the call-site list would become stale mid-iteration
and the candidate cost estimates (which depend on call-site context like
loop depth) could drift away from reality.

Cost-benefit heuristic in summary: a candidate proceeds only when the
modeled benefit (eliminated call overhead plus 20% of callee cost as a
proxy for enabled optimizations) exceeds the modeled cost (weighted
instruction count plus loop and exception penalties) by at least 5 units,
the absolute cost stays under 500 units, and we have not exceeded
max_inlining_depth nested inlines.

Recursion limit semantics: the depth counter is incremented before each
successful inline and decremented after, so nested inlining (where the
just-inlined body itself contained eligible calls) can still proceed up
to the limit. Direct self-recursion is filtered earlier in
create_inline_candidates by clearing can_inline, so the depth counter is
reserved for legitimate non-recursive inline chains.

Post-inline cleanup: perform_inline_transformation triggers SSA
recomputation when the context holds an SSA pointer, the candidate's
counters are folded into context statistics, and the entire context
(including caches and lists) is freed by destroy_inlining_context. The
caller (run_inlining_pass) is responsible for any subsequent optimization
passes that benefit from the now-inlined code (DCE, CSE, constant
propagation).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Main entry point for function inlining optimization.

Algorithm:
1. Create context
2. Collect call sites
3. Create candidates with cost analysis
4. Select profitable candidates
5. Perform inlining transformations
6. Recompute SSA
7. Print statistics
8. Clean up

Returns 1 on success, 0 on failure.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Worst-case complexity is O(C * (B_callee + I_callee)) where C is the
number of call sites in the function and B_callee/I_callee are the
average block and instruction counts of the inlined callees. The
cost_cache keeps cost analysis amortized O(1) per callee even with many
call sites. SSA recomputation, invoked from perform_inline_transformation,
is the dominant cost when many inlines fire; callers that perform many
inlines in sequence should consider batching SSA recomputation across the
whole pass.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The function refuses to operate on a null function pointer or a function
without a CFG, returning failure rather than dereferencing junk. Context
allocation failure is also handled. Every successful path frees the
context via destroy_inlining_context; the early-return paths after
"No calls found" also call destroy_inlining_context to prevent leaks.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "optimize_function_with_inlining" that takes function_ptr as Integer, program_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If function_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get CFG from function
    Let cfg_ptr be proc get_mir_function_cfg from MIR with function_ptr
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Display "Function has no CFG, skipping inlining"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create context
    Let context_ptr be proc create_inlining_context with cfg_ptr, program_ptr
    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Display "Failed to create inlining context"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set current function
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 24, function_ptr

    Note: Collect call sites
    Let call_count be proc collect_call_sites with context_ptr

    If call_count is equal to 0:
        proc destroy_inlining_context with context_ptr
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Create inline candidates
    Let candidate_count be proc create_inline_candidates with context_ptr

    Note: Inline profitable candidates
    Let candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 56
    Let inlined_count be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than candidate_count:
        Let candidate_ptr be proc get from List with candidates, i

        If candidate_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let is_profitable be proc is_profitable_to_inline with candidate_ptr, context_ptr

            If is_profitable is equal to 1:
                Note: Increment depth before inlining (track nesting level)
                Let current_depth be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 80
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 80, (current_depth plus 1)

                Let success be proc perform_inline_transformation with candidate_ptr, context_ptr

                Note: Decrement depth after inlining
                Let new_depth be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 80
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 80, (new_depth minus 1)

                If success is equal to 1:
                    Set inlined_count to inlined_count plus 1
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Update statistics
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 32, inlined_count

    Note: Clean up
    proc destroy_inlining_context with context_ptr

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Program-wide inlining is a per-function loop, not a fixed-point algorithm.
Each function is optimized independently with its own context, which means
the cost_cache does not carry across functions; this is the right trade-off
because cost analysis depends on the full callee body, which is invariant
across callers, but caching across the entire program would require
program-level memoization infrastructure beyond the scope of one pass.

External functions (is_external == 1) are skipped: their bodies are not
available in the current translation unit, so they cannot be inlined.
Walking the function list once with this filter is cheaper than producing
a filtered list up front because most production programs have very few
external definitions relative to internal ones.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Entry point for running inlining pass on entire program.

Returns 1 on success, 0 on failure.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Calling order matters: inlining works best after rough type inference and
basic constant propagation have run on each function (so cost estimates
reflect already-simplified code), but before global optimizations like
inter-procedural DCE (which benefit from the call-graph simplification
inlining produces). The reported optimized_count is informational; even
when zero inlines fire, the pass still consumes O(C) cost-analysis time
per function with C call sites.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "run_inlining_pass" that takes program_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If program_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get all functions
    Let functions be proc get_program_functions from MIRNodes with program_ptr
    If functions is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let func_count be proc length from List with functions
    Let optimized_count be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than func_count:
        Let func_ptr be proc get from List with functions, i

        If func_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let is_external be proc is_external_function from MIR with func_ptr
            If is_external is equal to 0:
                Let success be proc optimize_function_with_inlining with func_ptr, program_ptr
                If success is equal to 1:
                    Set optimized_count to optimized_count plus 1
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Inlining is gated to -O2 and above because at -O0/-O1 the debugger
experience suffers: stepping through inlined frames is confusing and
breakpoints on the original function definition become unreliable.
Additionally, the SSA recomputation cost only pays for itself when the
caller benefits from subsequent passes (DCE, CSE, constant folding) that
also run at -O2.

The early-out on functions without any calls (count_instructions_of_type
for MIR_CALL returns 0) avoids the constant overhead of building an
empty inlining context and walking an empty call-site list, which matters
in programs where most leaf functions have no calls of their own.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Profitability check for inlining optimization.

Inlining is beneficial when:
1. Function contains calls (has opportunities)
2. Optimization level > or equal to 2 (inlining at -O2 and above)
3. Not optimizing for size (-Os  skip aggressive inlining)

Returns 1 if should run, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "should_run_inlining" that takes function_ptr as Integer, optimization_level as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Inlining at -O2 and above
    If optimization_level is less than 2:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if function has calls
    If function_ptr is not equal to 0:
        Let call_count be proc count_instructions_of_type from MIRNodes with function_ptr, 20304
        If call_count is greater than 0:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: PASS METADATA
Note: ============================================================

@Implementation
Returns the name of this optimization pass.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_inlining_pass_name" that takes nothing returns Integer:
    Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Function Inlining"
End Process

@Implementation
Returns a description of this optimization pass.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_inlining_pass_description" that takes nothing returns Integer:
    Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Inlines function calls based on cost-benefit analysis to eliminate call overhead and enable inter-procedural optimization"
End Process
